lido:objectDescriptionSet.lido:descriptiveNoteValue: Altar to Neptune. The front of the shaft shows a vertical trident with a dolphin, the symbols of Neptune who to the Romans was a god of rivers and fresh water rather than the sea. The altar was probably made by the same hand as the altar to Oceanus (1903.6) also found in the Tyne. They were probably set up as a pair. It is thought that there was a shrine to the two gods on the bridge across the Tyne at Newcastle built at the point where the river under the protection of Neptune met the tidal waters of the sea under the protection of Oceanus. This bridge is considered to have been built on the instructions given by Hadrian during his visit to Britain in AD 122 being called the Pons Aelius after the family name of Hadrian. It is presumed that the shrine would have been contemporary with the bridge.

lido:objectDescriptionSet.lido:descriptiveNoteValue: Stone head of Antenociticus. Found with three altars in a shrine 61 metres from the east rampart of the fort at Benwell. The temple itself is situated in Broomridge Avenue. The sandstone head shows a beardless man with thick hair combed into locks over the forehead and ears with two strands trained from the crown of the head to the temples, like horns. A torc can be seen around the neck. Fragments of a forearm and lower leg were also found suggesting that a full life sized statue of the god was originally carved. The three altars all mention the name Antenociticus using various spellings so it may be presumed that this is the deity to whom the shrine was dedicated. He is unknown elsewhere in the Roman Empire and was probably a local god.
